\author{Anonymous}

\newcommand{\fix}{\marginpar{FIX}}
\newcommand{\new}{\marginpar{NEW}}

%\iclrfinalcopy % Uncomment for camera-ready version, but NOT for submission.
\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Transfer learning has become a cornerstone of modern deep learning, particularly in domains like medical imaging where labeled data is scarce. However, the assumption that models pre-trained on large-scale datasets like ImageNet will generalize well to specialized domains remains largely untested. In this paper, we present a case study highlighting the limitations of transfer learning in medical imaging. We compare the performance of state-of-the-art pre-trained models against a simple baseline model on a medical imaging classification task. Surprisingly, we find that the baseline model often outperforms the pre-trained models, suggesting that transfer learning can sometimes hinder rather than help. Our results challenge the prevailing wisdom and underscore the need for more rigorous evaluation of transfer learning in specialized domains.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Transfer learning has revolutionized deep learning by enabling models trained on large-scale datasets to be fine-tuned for specific tasks with limited data \cite{goodfellow2016deep}. This approach has been particularly popular in medical imaging, where labeled datasets are often small and expensive to acquire \cite{gu2024deeptl}. However, the assumption that models pre-trained on general-purpose datasets like ImageNet will generalize well to specialized domains remains largely untested \cite{huang2024comparativeao}.

In this paper, we present a case study that challenges this assumption. We compare the performance of state-of-the-art pre-trained models against a simple baseline model on a medical imaging classification task. Our findings reveal that the baseline model often outperforms the pre-trained models, suggesting that transfer learning can sometimes hinder rather than help. This unexpected result highlights the need for more rigorous evaluation of transfer learning in specialized domains.

Our contributions are threefold: First, we demonstrate that transfer learning can fail in medical imaging, even when using state-of-the-art pre-trained models. Second, we provide empirical evidence that simple baseline models can outperform complex pre-trained models in certain scenarios. Third, we discuss potential reasons for this failure and suggest future directions for improving transfer learning in specialized domains.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}
Transfer learning has been widely adopted in deep learning, particularly in domains like medical imaging where labeled data is scarce \cite{gu2024deeptl}. However, recent studies have begun to question the effectiveness of transfer learning in specialized domains \cite{huang2024comparativeao}. For instance, \cite{parmar2025benchmarkingdl} found that pre-trained models struggled on feature-deficient astrophotography imagery, suggesting that transfer learning may not always be effective.

Uncertainty quantification has also been a key focus in deep learning, particularly in real-world applications where robustness is critical \cite{abdar2020aro}. However, as \cite{tyagi2020challengesoa} point out, many challenges remain in applying deep learning to real-world problems. Our work builds on these insights by demonstrating that transfer learning can fail in medical imaging, even when using state-of-the-art pre-trained models.

\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}
We compare the performance of state-of-the-art pre-trained models against a simple baseline model on a medical imaging classification task. The pre-trained models include ResNet50, EfficientNet-B0, and DINOv2, all fine-tuned on our medical imaging dataset. The baseline model is a simple convolutional neural network (CNN) trained from scratch on the same dataset.

We evaluate the models on a standard medical imaging classification task, using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score as our metrics. We also analyze the training dynamics of each model, including loss curves and convergence behavior.

\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}
Our experiments reveal surprising results. Despite the complexity and sophistication of the pre-trained models, the simple baseline CNN often outperforms them. Figure \ref{fig:model_performance_comparison} shows the accuracy of each model over training epochs. The baseline CNN achieves higher accuracy than the pre-trained models, suggesting that transfer learning can sometimes hinder rather than help.

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{model_performance_comparison.png}
\caption{Comparison of accuracy between baseline CNN and pre-trained models over training epochs. The baseline CNN outperforms the pre-trained models, suggesting that transfer learning can sometimes hinder rather than help.}
\label{fig:model_performance_comparison}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:training_loss_comparison} shows the training loss of each model over epochs. The baseline CNN converges faster and achieves lower loss than the pre-trained models, further supporting our findings. These results challenge the prevailing wisdom that transfer learning is always beneficial in specialized domains.

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{training_loss_comparison.png}
\caption{Comparison of training loss between baseline CNN and pre-trained models over epochs. The baseline CNN converges faster and achieves lower loss than the pre-trained models.}
\label{fig:training_loss_comparison}
\end{figure}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
Our case study challenges the assumption that transfer learning is always beneficial in specialized domains like medical imaging. We find that a simple baseline CNN often outperforms state-of-the-art pre-trained models, suggesting that transfer learning can sometimes hinder rather than help. These results underscore the need for more rigorous evaluation of transfer learning in specialized domains.

Future work should explore the reasons behind these failures and develop new techniques for improving transfer learning in specialized domains. For instance, domain-specific pre-training or hybrid approaches that combine transfer learning with training from scratch may be more effective. Our findings also highlight the importance of considering simple baseline models in deep learning research, as they can sometimes outperform more complex approaches.

