\begin{abstract}
Deep learning models often exhibit high confidence in their predictions, even when they are incorrect. This overconfidence can lead to unexpected failures in real-world applications, particularly in scenarios requiring robust generalization. In this paper, we investigate the pitfalls of overconfidence in deep learning models through a series of experiments. We compare the performance of a baseline model with a proposed method designed to mitigate overconfidence. Surprisingly, our results show that the proposed method fails to consistently improve generalization, despite theoretical underpinnings suggesting otherwise. We analyze these unexpected results and discuss implications for future research in model calibration and uncertainty quantification. Our findings highlight the challenges of translating theoretical advancements into practical improvements and underscore the need for more rigorous evaluation of deep learning methods in real-world settings.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Deep learning has achieved remarkable success across various domains, from computer vision to natural language processing \cite{goodfellow2016deep}. However, the deployment of deep learning models in real-world applications often reveals unexpected failures, particularly in scenarios requiring robust generalization. One such failure mode is overconfidence, where models exhibit high confidence in incorrect predictions. This overconfidence can lead to catastrophic consequences in critical applications such as healthcare and autonomous systems.

In this paper, we investigate the pitfalls of overconfidence in deep learning models. We conduct a series of experiments comparing a baseline model with a proposed method designed to mitigate overconfidence. Our results reveal unexpected failures in the proposed method, challenging the prevailing assumptions about model calibration and uncertainty quantification. These findings underscore the importance of rigorous evaluation and the need for new approaches to address overconfidence in deep learning models.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}
Previous work has highlighted the challenges of overconfidence and uncertainty quantification in deep learning models \cite{borotikar2025accuraciesua}. Bayesian methods and evidential deep learning have been proposed as solutions to improve model reliability and uncertainty estimation \cite{khot2025evidentialdl, valiuddin2024aro}. However, these methods often fail to generalize across different domains and datasets \cite{chen2024deeplearningbasedlb, corso2025foundationmf}.

Domain generalization frameworks have been developed to address these challenges, but their effectiveness remains limited in practice \cite{turkulainen2025domaingi}. Adversarial attacks further exacerbate the problem, highlighting the fragility of deep learning models \cite{zhou2022adversarialaa}. Recent work on interpretability has shown promise in improving model transparency, but the relationship between interpretability and overconfidence remains poorly understood \cite{almadhor2025anix}.

\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}
Our proposed method aims to mitigate overconfidence by incorporating uncertainty quantification into the training process. We modify the loss function to penalize overconfident predictions, encouraging the model to express uncertainty when appropriate. This approach is inspired by Bayesian methods but avoids the computational complexity associated with traditional Bayesian inference.

The modified loss function combines the standard cross-entropy loss with an additional term that penalizes overconfidence. The penalty term is proportional to the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the predicted probability distribution and a uniform distribution, which represents maximum uncertainty. This encourages the model to express uncertainty in ambiguous situations, potentially improving generalization.

\section{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:experimental_setup}
We evaluate our method on a standard image classification task using the CIFAR-10 dataset. We train a convolutional neural network (CNN) as the baseline model and compare its performance with our proposed method. Both models are trained for 100 epochs using the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001.

To assess generalization, we evaluate the models on both the training set and a held-out test set. We measure accuracy, loss, and calibration error to quantify model performance and overconfidence. Calibration error is computed using the Expected Calibration Error (ECE), which measures the difference between predicted confidence and empirical accuracy.

\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}
Our experiments reveal unexpected results. While the proposed method reduces overconfidence on the training set, it fails to improve generalization on the test set. Figure \ref{fig:training_loss_comparison} shows the training loss comparison between the baseline and proposed methods. The proposed method achieves lower training loss, suggesting better calibration.

However, Figure \ref{fig:accuracy_vs_epoch} shows that both methods achieve similar accuracy on the test set, indicating that the proposed method does not improve generalization. Figure \ref{fig:ablation_study_results} presents the results of an ablation study, which confirms that the additional penalty term does not consistently improve performance.

These results challenge the prevailing assumptions about model calibration and uncertainty quantification. While the proposed method successfully reduces overconfidence on the training set, it fails to translate this improvement into better generalization on unseen data. This highlights the complexity of addressing overconfidence in deep learning models and underscores the need for more rigorous evaluation methods.

