\caption{Accuracy vs. Epoch. Both methods achieve similar accuracy on the test set, indicating that the proposed method does not improve generalization.}
\label{fig:accuracy_vs_epoch}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{ablation_study_results.png}
\caption{Ablation Study Results. The additional penalty term does not consistently improve performance, highlighting the complexity of addressing overconfidence.}
\label{fig:ablation_study_results}
\end{figure}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
Our investigation into the pitfalls of overconfidence in deep learning models reveals unexpected failures in a proposed method designed to mitigate overconfidence. Despite theoretical underpinnings suggesting improved calibration and generalization, our experiments show that the proposed method fails to consistently improve performance on unseen data.

These findings underscore the challenges of translating theoretical advancements into practical improvements and highlight the need for more rigorous evaluation methods. Future research should focus on developing more robust approaches to address overconfidence, particularly in real-world applications where reliable uncertainty quantification is critical.

